":"1338","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","about 1375":"circa 1375","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"England","Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Southampton, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1300–1375":"1300–1375","1310–1375":"1310–1375","1338–1437":"1338–1437","1270–1356":"1270–1356","1280–Female":"1280–Deceased","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1338":"1338","1437":"1437","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","about 1375":"about 1375","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"England","Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drewe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  See  Drew  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Drew","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from a Norman French personal name <i>Dreus</i> based on ancient Germanic <i>Drogo</i>, the name of one of the sons of Charlemagne (compare Gothic <i>driugan</i> ‘to serve as a soldier’). In Old French this name became <i>Dreus</i>, <i>Drues</i> (nominative) and <i>Dru</i>, <i>Driu</i>, <i>Dreu</i> (accusative) and was introduced to England by the Normans. For further information about this name, see also   Montague  .","English: from the personal name <i>Drew</i>, a pet form of   Andrew   which was confused with the same name of Old French origin (see 1 above).","Irish: when not an adoption of the English surname, a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Druaidh</b> or <b>Ó Druaidh</b> or <b>Ó Draoi</b> ‘son’ and ‘descendant of the druid’, from <i>draoi</i> ‘druid’, genitive <i>druadh</i> or <i>draoi</i>. All of these were often Anglicized as   Drury  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When William Drewe was born in 1300, in England, his father, John Elias Drewe, was 30 and his mother, Mathilde Virtue, was 20. He married Eleanor de Kingston. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1375, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1300–1375":"1300–1375","1310–1375":"1310–